    pearls: ["NEVER examine the throat of a child with suspected epiglottitis using a tongue blade or direct visualization outside of a controlled setting -- this can trigger laryngospasm and precipitate complete airway obstruction and cardiac arrest; the diagnosis in children is clinical + lateral neck X-ray (if stable)","The 'four Ds' of epiglottitis in children are Drooling, Dysphagia, Dysphonia (muffled voice), and Distress; combined with acute high fever and the tripod position, this presentation demands IMMEDIATE airway management before any other intervention","Epiglottitis vs. croup (laryngotracheobronchitis): croup has gradual onset (1-2 days of URI prodrome), barking cough, lower-grade fever, and steeple sign on X-ray; epiglottitis has abrupt onset (hours), NO cough, high fever, drooling, and thumbprint sign on X-ray; croup responds to racemic epinephrine and dexamethasone, while epiglottitis requires airway management and IV antibiotics","In adults, epiglottitis may present more subtly with severe sore throat, odynophagia, and anterior neck tenderness; adults can often be managed with close monitoring, IV antibiotics, and humidified oxygen WITHOUT intubation if there are no signs of airway compromise; however, intubation equipment must be immediately available","The thumbprint sign on lateral neck X-ray (swollen, rounded epiglottis) is a classic finding but has only ~80% sensitivity; a normal lateral neck film does NOT rule out epiglottitis; if clinical suspicion is high, proceed with fiberoptic visualization in a controlled setting","Post-Hib vaccine era: adult epiglottitis cases now outnumber pediatric cases; the NP should maintain a high index of suspicion for epiglottitis in adults presenting with severe sore throat disproportionate to pharyngeal findings, especially with anterior neck tenderness and inability to swallow"],
